The brutality of Russia's drone assaults on Ukraine's towns and cities shows no let up. "Savage strikes, a deliberate targeted terror" is how the Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy described the latest overnight bombardment. Some 595 attack drones and 48 missiles were involved and even if only a small fraction made it through Ukrainian air defences, the destruction - in Sumy and Odessa, Zaporizhia and Kyiv - is significant.    Also overnight, Denmark reported yet more drone sightings. It has not named Russia directly but after a week in which unidentified drones have resulted in the temporary shutdown of military and civilian airports, it is banning all civil drone flights and describing the threat as a hybrid attack. Germany is also raising the alarm over unexplained drone activity along its border with Denmark. Germany's interior minister said on Saturday: "We are witnessing an arms race, an arms race between drone threats and drone defences. It is a race we cannot afford to lose." NATO is having to deploy extra assets to beef up its Baltic Sea defences and its Eastern flank. European nations are working to establish a drone wall along their borders with Russia and Ukraine. Germany is setting up a drone defence centre to make sure it has what it needs to protect itself. The Kremlin is forcing NATO to divert assets to protect its airspace and sub-sea infrastructure at a time when Europe is trying to work out how best to support and finance Ukraine. Read more:Putin's top diplomat issues warningWhy Trump has made a U-turn With drones an inexpensive element of its hybrid warfare arsenal, Russia is sending a clear warning that it can relatively easily chip away at Europe's defences and that Europe had better focus on protecting itself. "If NATO begins to look too rattled, that actually is encouragement for Putin precisely to step up the pressure," says Mark Galeotti, a specialist in Russian security. "So really we need to be holding our nerve. "Yes, reserving the right to shoot things down that look like direct threats, but otherwise actually talking down, not talking up, the nature of the threat while of course we arm so that we are even more prepared." Last week, Estonia said its fighter jets had escorted three Russian MIG fighter jets out of their airspace after a 12-minute incursion, which Russia denies ever took place.  On Saturday, Estonia pledged €10m (£8.7m) to NATO's "Prioritised Ukraine Requirement List" or PURL programme, which sees US-produced weapons, paid for by NATO's European partners, fast-tracked to Ukraine. Zelenskyy posted on Sunday after speaking with the NATO secretary general that PURL is moving forward well. And that is just what Russia is trying to prevent.

        National correspondent
            @TomSkyNews
England’s Red Roses promised they would celebrate hard after their World Cup win, and they kept their word. The hoarse throats, sore heads and never-ending smiles on Sunday confirmed they'd had the night of their lives. They strode out onto the balcony at the front of Battersea Power Station, southwest London, on Sunday afternoon, lapping up the love from thousands of fans who had gathered in the rain to share the celebrations. Player of the match in the final, flanker Sadia Kabeya, told Sky News it had been a big night: "You can't go home until [captain] Zoe Aldcroft goes home and that girl stays out late."  "So, as you can imagine, it was a long night, but it was great night," she continued. "You know, we've got to celebrate. This happens, you know, what, once every four years or so." The team's victory over Canada in front of a world record-breaking crowd of 81,885 at Twickenham on Saturday represents a huge milestone for the game.  Rugby fan Akua, from London, bagged a last-minute ticket to the final and said it was "magical, inspiring and empowering". "We just need to keep inspiring young girls and get them to keep believing in themselves," she added. Rachel Baxter travelled down from Liverpool and had also thrown herself into the post-match celebrations. She said: "It is just amazing, it has been building so much. I was looking at the stands yesterday and there were no gaps, and I got a bit emotional. "I am so proud it bursts your heart." It hasn't happened by chance. The Rugby Football Union (RFU) has backed the women's game with record investment and the Red Roses are the best-funded women's rugby team on earth - but they still had to win it. They saved their best performance of the tournament for the World Cup final and will now reap the rewards and hope the game continues to grow. Read more: Royals - and Russell Crowe - lead congratulations Among the crowd was Lucy Bronze, a key player in the Lionesses football team that won the Euros again this summer, said she hoped the Red Roses enjoy the glory and embrace the opportunity it brings. "We want to help lift little girls up, we want to help show little boys what girls are capable of," Bronze said. "Being here today to celebrate them, I know they're huge fans of the Lionesses as well - and just celebrating strong powerful women being successful is just so good for the nation." Double Olympic champion Dame Kelly Holmes joined the celebrations too after watching the final against Canada on Saturday. "I didn't know much about women's rugby, yesterday I was there, now I'm a big fan," she said. "So I just hope that we keep the momentum going... the Lionesses, the rugby women, the Red Roses, they brought like this pride in England. "I saw the English flag being flown yesterday - that's why we fly the English flag, because we're proud of who we are - because sport is what brings us together." The Red Roses carried their trophy off stage and went down to meet friends, family and their growing army of fans. It's the party that none of them want to leave.

